> `GinkgoT().Chdir` does not internally verify and fail the test on error, this change could allow directory change errors to go unnoticed.

Actually, `GinkgoT().Chdir()` does verify and fail the test on error. Looking at the implementation https://github.com/onsi/ginkgo/blob/1333dae491f7bcac59f35e0c524d9884227bcf2b/internal/testingtproxy/testing_t_proxy.go#L84-L96:

```go
func (t *ginkgoTestingTProxy) Chdir(dir string) {
	currentDir, err := os.Getwd()
	if err != nil {
		t.fail(fmt.Sprintf("Failed to get current directory: %v", err), 1)
	}

	t.cleanup(os.Chdir, currentDir, internal.Offset(1))

	err = os.Chdir(dir)
	if err != nil {
		t.fail(fmt.Sprintf("Failed to change directory: %v", err), 1)
	}
}
```

The `Chdir` method internally calls `fail()` if there's an error, which will properly fail the test.
